  "title": "URI Routing",
  "story": [
    {
      "text": "Typically there is a one-to-one relationship between a URL string and its corresponding controller/handler. The segments in a URI normally follow this pattern:",
      "id": "0ce10b2b2423933b",
      "type": "paragraph"
    },
    {
      "text": "example.com/controller/handler/id/",
      "id": "8238cf20d4009349",
      "type": "code"
    },
    {
      "text": "In some instances, however, you may want to remap this relationship so that a different controller/handler can be called instead of the one corresponding to the URL.",
      "id": "4bee945292ffd6fe",
      "type": "paragraph"
    },
    {
      "text": "For example, lets say you want your URLs to have this prototype:",
      "id": "5344d884fab61b32",
      "type": "paragraph"
    },
    {
      "text": "example.com/product/1/\nexample.com/product/2/\nexample.com/product/3/\nexample.com/product/4/",
      "id": "f2d101215bd6313d",
      "type": "code"
    },
    {
      "text": "Normally the second segment of the URL is reserved for the handler name, but in the example above it instead has a product ID. To overcome this, revIgniter allows you to remap the URI handler.",
      "id": "1787452e8d6868be",
      "type": "paragraph"
    },
